President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to appoint several individuals to key positions in his Administration. Darlene Hutchinson of Alabama will be appointed as Director of the Office of Victims of Crime, Department of Justice. Hutchinson has over 20 years of experience as a crime victims' advocate and has worked extensively on legislation and public policy related to victims' rights. She has also volunteered with rape crisis centers and served as the editor of law enforcement publications. Hutchinson has played a key role in the development of Alabama's victim notification system and the passage of a Victims' Constitutional Amendment. Hans A. Von Spakovsky of Virginia will be appointed as a Member of the Presidential Advisory Commission on Election Integrity.

In addition to these appointments, President Trump has nominated Matthew P. Donovan of Virginia to be Under Secretary of the Air Force. Donovan has served in various roles related to national security and defense policy, including as majority policy director for the U.S. Senate Committee on Armed Services. He also has 31 years of experience in the Air Force, retiring as a colonel. Eric S. Dreiband of Maryland has been nominated to be an Assistant Attorney General in the Civil Rights Division of the Department of Justice. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas has been nominated to be the United States Permanent Representative on the Council of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), with the rank and status of Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary. Hutchison has extensive experience in international affairs, serving as a U.S. Senator and as vice chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board.

These nominations and appointments reflect President Trump's ongoing efforts to fill key positions in his Administration.